7 Serie A|2016\u201317]], [[2017\u201318 Serie A|2017\u201318]], [[2018\u201319 Serie A|2018\u201319]]\n* [[Coppa Italia]] (4): [[2014\u201315 Coppa Italia|2014\u201315]], [[2015\u201316 Coppa Italia|2015\u201316]], [[2016\u201317 Coppa Italia|2016\u201317]], [[2017\u201318 Coppa Italia|2017\u201318]]\n* [[Supercoppa Italiana]] (2): [[2015 Supercoppa Italiana|2015]], [[2018 Supercoppa Italiana|2018]]\n* [[UEFA Champions League]] Runner-up: [[2014\u201315 UEFA Champions League|2014\u201315]], [[2016\u201317 UEFA Champions League|2016\u201317]] <!-- hold -->\n\n=== Individual ===\n* Panchina d'Oro Prima Divisione (1): [[2007\u201308 Serie C1|2007\u201308]]<ref name=uefa.com/>\n* [[Panchina d'Oro]] (4): [[2008\u201309 Serie A|2008\u201309]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/52242/allegri%E2%80%99s-opportunity-juve%E2%80%99s-gain|title=Allegri\u2019s opportunity, Juve\u2019s gain?|publisher=Football Italia|date=17 July 2014|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref> [[2014\u201315 Serie A|2014\u201315]],<ref name=juvepanchia/> [[2016\u201317 Serie A|2016\u201317]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/119041/allegri-wins-2017-panchina-doro|title=Allegri wins 2017 Panchina d\u2019Oro|publisher=Football Italia|date=26 March 2018|accessdate=26 March 2018}}</ref> [[2017\u201318 Serie A|2017\u201318]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.juventus.com/en/news/news/2018/allegri-named-best-manager-in-italy-for-the-fourth-time.php|title=Allegri named best manager in Italy for the fourth time!|publisher=juventus.com|date=12 November 2018|accessdate=12 November 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Serie A Coach of the Year]] (4): [[2010\u201311 Serie A|2011]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/12040/9383781/serie-a-juventus-appoint-massimiliano-allegri-as-new-coach|title=Serie A: Juventus appoint Massimiliano Allegri as new coach|publisher=Sky Sports|date=16 July 2014|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref> [[2014\u201315 Serie A|2015]],<ref name=\"Sport Mediaset\"/> [[2015\u201316 Serie A|2016]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.sky.it/calcio/serie-a/2017/01/30/gran-gala-del-calcio-2017-premiati.html|title=Gran Gal\u00e0 del calcio, la notte delle stelle|publisher=Sky.it|language=Italian|date=30 January 2017|accessdate=31 January 2017}}</ref> [[2017\u201318 Serie A|2018]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/131572/allegri-wins-serie-coach-year|title=Allegri wins Serie A Coach of the Year|publisher=Football Italia|date=3 December 2018|accessdate=3 December 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Enzo Bearzot Award]] (1): 2015<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vivoazzurro.it/en/figcnews/e-allegri-il-vincitore-del-premio-bearzot-la-premiazione-il-25-maggio-al-coni-2/|title=Allegri wins Bearzot award|publisher=Vivo Azzurro|date=25 March 2015|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref>\n* [[IFFHS World's Best Club Coach]]: 2015 (third place),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/leo-messi-and-luis-enrique-honoured-by-iffhs|title=Leo Messi and Luis Enrique honoured by IFFHS|publisher=FC Barcelona|accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref> 2017 (second place)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/leo-messi-and-luis-enrique-honoured-by-iffhs|title=Leo Messi and Luis Enrique honoured by IFFHS|publisher=FC Barcelona|accessdate=4 January 2017}}</ref>\n* [[The Best FIFA Football Coach#Men.27s winners|The Best FIFA Men's Coach]]: [[The Best FIFA Football Awards 2017#The Best FIFA Men.27s Coach|2017]] (third place)<ref name=\"2017 The Best FIFA Men's Coach\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/the-best-fifa-football-awards/best-fifa-mens-coach/index.html|title=The Best FIFA Men's Coach|publisher=FIFA.com|accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Gazzetta Sports Awards]] \u2013 Coach of the Year: 2018<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Sport-Vari/04-12-2018/gazzetta-sports-awards-2018-premiazione-sportivi-anno-310980454325.shtml |title=Gazzetta Sports Awards 2018: Tortu \u00e8 l'Uomo dell'anno, bis per la Goggia. ItalVolley femminile, squadra top |publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=Italian |date=4 December 2018 |accessdate=5 December 2018 }}</ref>\n* [[Italian Football Hall of Fame]]: 2018<ref name=\"2018-SerieAHoF\">{{cite web|url=https://www.figc.it/it/formazione-ed-eventi/news/totti-zanetti-e-allegri-tra-i-premiati-dell-8-edizione-della-hall-of-fame-del-calcio-italiano/|title=Totti, Zanetti e Allegri tra i premiati dell\u20198\u00aa edizione della 'Hall of Fame del calcio italiano'|publisher=FIGC.it|language=Italian|date=19 February 2019|accessdate=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{UEFA coach|22734|Massimiliano Allegri}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Massimiliano Allegri managerial positions\n|list1=\n{{U.S. Sassuolo Calcio managers}}\n{{Cagliari Calcio managers}}\n{{A.C. Milan managers}}\n{{Juventus F.C. managers}}\n}}\n{{Serie A Coach of the Year}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{portal bar|Association football|Italy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Allegri, Massimiliano}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Livorno]]\n[[Category:Italian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:A.S. Livorno Calcio players]]\n[[Category:A.C. Pisa 1909 players]]\n[[Category:Delfino Pescara 1936 players]]\n[[Category:Cagliari Calcio players]]\n[[Category:A.C. Perugia Calcio players]]\n[[Category:Calcio Padova players]]\n[[Category:S.S.C. Napoli players]]\n[[Category:U.S. Pistoiese 1921 players]]\n[[Category:F.C. Pavia players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Serie B players]]\n[[Category:Serie C players]]\n[[Category:Serie D players]]\n[[Category:Italian football managers]]\n[[Category:S.P.A.L. managers]]\n[[Category:F.C. Grosseto S.S.D. managers]]\n[[Category:U.S. Sassuolo Calcio managers]]\n[[Category:Cagliari Calcio managers]]\n[[Category:A.C. Milan managers]]\n[[Category:Juventus F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Serie C managers]]\n[[Category:Serie A managers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Pro Licence holders]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n | name                 = Massimiliano Allegri \n | image                = Allegri with Milan players (cropped) - 2.jpg\n | image_size           = 200px\n | caption              = Allegri as manager of [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] in 2012\n | fullname             = Massimiliano Allegri\n | birth_date           = {{birth date and age|1967|8|11|df=y}}\n | birth_place          = [[Livorno]], Italy\n | height               = {{height|m=1.83}}\n | currentclub          =\n | position             = [[Midfielder]]\n | years1  = 1984\u20131985 | clubs1  = Cuoiopelli | caps1  =  7 | goals1  =  0\n | years2  = 1985\u20131988 | clubs2  = [[A.S. Livorno Calcio|Livorno]]              | caps2  = 29 | goals2  =  0\n | years3  = 1988\u20131989 | clubs3  = [[A.C. Pisa 1909|Pisa]]                      | caps3  =  2 | goals3  =  0\n | years4  = 1989\u20131990 | clubs4  = [[A.S. Livorno Calcio|Livorno]]              | caps4  = 32 | goals4  =  8\n | years5  = 1990\u20131991 | clubs5  = [[A.C. Pavia|Pavia]]                         | caps5  = 29 | goals5  =  5\n | years6  = 1991\u20131993 | clubs6  = [[Pescara Calcio|Pescara]]                   | caps6  = 64 | goals6  = 16\n | years7  = 1993\u20131995 | clubs7  = [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]]                 | caps7  = 46 | goals7  =  4\n | years8  = 1995\u20131997 | clubs8  = [[Perugia Calcio|Perugia]]                   | caps8  = 41 | goals8  = 10\n | years9  = 1997\u20131998 | clubs9  = [[Calcio Padova|Padova]]                     | caps9  = 21 | goals9  =  0\n | years10 = 1998      | clubs10 = [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]]                     | caps10 =  7 | goals10 =  0\n | years11 = 1998\u20132000 | clubs11 = [[Pescara Calcio|Pescara]]                   | caps11 = 46 | goals11 =  4\n | years12 = 2000\u20132001 | clubs12 = [[A.C. Pistoiese|Pistoiese]]                 | caps12 = 18 | goals12 =  1\n | years13 = 2001\u20132003 | clubs13 = [[Aglianese Calcio 1923|Aglianese]]          | caps13 = 32 | goals13 =  8\n | totalcaps = 374 | totalgoals = 56\n | manageryears1 = 2003\u20132004 | managerclubs1 = [[Aglianese Calcio 1923|Aglianese]]\n | manageryears2 = 2004\u20132005 | managerclubs2 = [[S.P.A.L. 2013|SPAL]]\n | manageryears3 = 2005\u20132006 | managerclubs3 = [[F.C. Grosseto S.S.D.|Grosseto]]\n | manageryears4 = 2007\u20132008 | managerclubs4 = [[U.S. Sassuolo Calcio|Sassuolo]]\n | manageryears5 = 2008\u20132010 | managerclubs5 = [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]]\n | manageryears6 = 2010\u20132014 | managerclubs6 = [[A.C. Milan|Milan]]\n | manageryears7 = 2014\u20132019 | managerclubs7 = [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]\n}}\n'''Massimiliano \"Max\" Allegri''' ({{IPA-it|massimi\u02c8lja\u02d0no al\u02c8le\u02d0\u0261ri, - al\u02c8l\u025b\u02d0-}};<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dipionline.it/dizionario/ricerca?lemma=Massimiliano|title=Massimiliano|work=DiPI Online|author=[[Luciano Canepari]]|accessdate=26 October 2018|language=it}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dipionline.it/dizionario/ricerca?lemma=Allegri|title=Allegri|work=DiPI Online|author=Luciano Canepari|accessdate=26 October 2018|language=it}}</ref> born 11 August 1967) is an Italian former professional [[Association football|football]] player and current [[Manager (association football)|manager]], who most recently managed [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]].\n\nAs a player, Allegri was a [[midfielder]] who spent his career playing for various Italian clubs. After beginning his managerial career in 2003 with several smaller Italian sides, he later played a key role in [[U.S. Sassuolo Calcio|Sassuolo]]'s rise through the lower Italian divisions and subsequently led [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]] to their best Serie A finish in nearly 15 years, winning the [[Panchina d'Oro]] Award for best Serie A coach in [[2008\u201309 Serie A|2009]]. His performances as head coach of Cagliari earned him a move to [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] in 2010, where he remained until January 2014; in the [[2010\u201311 Serie A|2010\u201311 season]], Allegri helped Milan to their first Serie A title since the 2003\u201304 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/SPORT/football/05/07/milan.serie.a.champions/index.html|title=Milan crowned Serie A champions after Roma draw|work=[[CNN News]]|accessdate=28 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter joining Juventus in 2014, he won four consecutive domestic [[Double (association football)|doubles]] between 2015 and 2018, the only coach to achieve this feat in the top 5 European leagues.\n\n== Club career ==\nAfter spending the earlier part of his career in the lower leagues, including his hometown club [[A.S. Livorno Calcio|Livorno]], Allegri joined [[Pescara Calcio|Pescara]] in 1991. A talented and creative player, he established himself in midfield as [[Giovanni Galeone]]'s side won promotion to [[Serie A]] in 1992. Allegri was an outstanding performer for Pescara in Serie A. Despite the side's relegation in last place, there was no shortage of goals and Allegri scored an impressive 12 goals from midfield. He moved on to [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]] and then [[Perugia Calcio|Perugia]] and [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]] before returning to Pescara. Brief spells at [[A.C. Pistoiese|Pistoiese]] and [[Aglianese Calcio 1923|Aglianese]] followed before his retirement from active football in 2003.<ref name=uefa.com>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=1503391.html|title=Massimiliano Allegri|publisher=UEFA.com|date=1 July 2015|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was banned for one year in 2001 with another six Italian footballers for match-fixing following a [[Coppa Italia]] tie in 2000. The [[Italian Football Federation]] (FIGC) also handed one-year suspensions to [[Fabio Gallo]], [[Sebastiano Siviglia]], and [[Luciano Zauri]] of Serie A side [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]]; and [[Alfredo Aglietti]] of [[Serie B]]'s Pistoiese.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/1238304.stm|title=Six Italians banned for match-fixing|publisher=BBC|date=23 March 2001|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Managerial career ==\n=== Early career ===\nAllegri started his managerial career in 2004, serving as the manager of [[Lega Pro Seconda Divisione|Serie C2]] team [[Aglianese Calcio 1923|Aglianese]], the club where he spent his two final years as a player. Following an impressive season with them, Allegri was called to head [[U.S. Grosseto F.C.|Grosseto]], then in [[Serie C1]], but his experience with the ''biancazzurri'' proved not to be as successful as with Aglianese and he was ultimately sacked shortly after the beginning of the 2006\u201307 Serie C1 season. Shortly after being sacked by Grosseto, Allegri agreed to rejoin his mentor [[Giovanni Galeone]] at [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]], becoming part of his coaching staff.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sportnews.it/news/index.php?nid=2056480&srctxt= |publisher=SportNews.it |language=Italian |title=Udinese, Allegri entra nello staff tecnico come ottimizzatore |accessdate=28 April 2008|date=6 November 2008}}{{dead link|date=September 2010}}</ref> However, this practice proved to be forbidden by the Italian football laws because he was still contracted with the Tuscan club, which caused Allegri to be disqualified for three months in early 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.unionesportivafoggia.com/index.php?id=2533 |publisher=Foggia Calcio |language=Italian |title=Allegri il prigioniero. Tra venti giorni esce |accessdate=28 April 2008 |date=14 March 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090418153455/http://www.unionesportivafoggia.com/index.php?id=2533 |archivedate=18 April 2009 }}</ref>\n\n=== Sassuolo ===\nIn August 2007, Allegri became head coach of ambitious [[Serie C1]] team [[U.S. Sassuolo Calcio|Sassuolo]], who Allegri managed to lead quickly into the top league spots. On 27 April 2008, Sassuolo mathematically ensured the 2007\u201308 Serie C1/A league title, thus winning a historical first promotion to [[Serie B]] for the ''neroverdi''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.repubblica.it/2008/04/sezioni/sport/calcio/ritornano-in-b/ritornano-in-b/ritornano-in-b.html |publisher=La Repubblica |title=Sassuolo e Salernitana in serie B, promozione storica per gli emiliani |accessdate=27 April 2008|date=27 April 2008|language=Italian}}</ref>\n\n=== Cagliari ===\nOn 29 May 2008, Allegri was announced as new head coach of [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]] in the [[Serie A]], replacing [[Davide Ballardini]].<ref name=\"allegri_cagliari\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cagliaricalcio.net/news/notizia.asp?idNotizia=5599&type=0&id_menu=1 |language=Italian |publisher=Cagliari Calcio |accessdate=29 May 2008 |date=29 May 2008 |title=Allegri sulla panchina del Cagliari |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080601211839/http://www.cagliaricalcio.net/news/notizia.asp?idNotizia=5599&type=0&id_menu=1 |archivedate=1 June 2008}}</ref> Despite a disappointing start, with five losses in the first five league matches, Allegri was confirmed by club chairman [[Massimo Cellino]] and later went on to bring his team up to a mid-table placement in December.<ref name=relationship>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/club/juventus/111/blog/post/1953467/allegri-needs-to-fix-pirlo-relationship|title=Allegri needs to fix Pirlo relationship|publisher=ESPN FC|author1=James Horncastle|date=18 July 2014|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref> On 9 December, following a 1\u20130 home win to [[U.S. Citt\u00e0 di Palermo|Palermo]], Cagliari announced they had agreed a two-year contract extension with Allegri, with a new contract that was set to expire on 1 June 2011. The contract was then revealed to have been signed in October, in the midst of the ''rossoblu'''s early crisis.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tuttomercatoweb.com/index.php?action=read&id=131831 |publisher=TuttoMercatoWeb |language=Italian |accessdate=13 December 2008 |date=9 December 2008|title=Il Cagliari conferma Allegri fino al 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe completed the [[2008\u201309 Serie A|2008\u201309 season]] in an impressive ninth place, their best result in Serie A in almost fifteen years, which was hailed as a huge result in light of the limited resources, the lack of top-class players, and the high quality of Cagliari's attacking football style, which led the [[Sardinia]]ns not far from [[UEFA Europa League]] qualification.<ref name=relationship/> Such results led him to be awarded the [[Panchina d'Oro]] ''(Golden bench)'', a prize awarded to the best Serie A football manager according to other managers' votes, ahead of Serie A winning coach [[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]].<ref name=relationship/> In the [[2009\u201310 Serie A|2009\u201310 season]], he managed to confirm Cagliari's high footballing levels despite the loss of regular striker [[Robert Acquafresca]], leading an impressive number of three players from his side\u2014namely [[Davide Biondini]], [[Federico Marchetti]], and [[Andrea Cossu (footballer, born 1980)|Andrea Cossu]]\u2014to receive [[Italy national football team|Italian national team]] call-ups during his reign at the club.\n\nOn 13 April 2010, Cagliari surprisingly removed Allegri from his managerial duties despite a solid 12th place with 40 points, and youth coach Giorgio Melis\u2014with [[Gianluca Festa]] as his assistant\u2014was appointed as his replacement.<ref name=\"allegri_sacked\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cagliaricalcio.net/news/notizia.asp?idNotizia=8572&type=0&id_menu=1 |publisher=Cagliari Calcio |language=Italian |accessdate=13 April 2010 |date=13 April 2010 |title=Esonerato Allegri |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100426015307/http://www.cagliaricalcio.net/news/notizia.asp?idNotizia=8572&type=0&id_menu=1 |archivedate=26 April 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/10/italy/2010/04/13/1877346/official-cagliari-sack-coach-massimiliano-allegri|title=OFFICIAL: Cagliari Sack Coach Massimiliano Allegri|date=13 April 2010|work=Goal.com|publisher=Ellinton Invest Inc.|first=Rick|last=D'Andrea|accessdate=13 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Milan ===\n[[File:Allegri with Robinho.jpg|thumb|262px|Allegri with [[Mario Yepes]] and [[Robinho]] in 2012]]\nAllegri was released from his contract by Cagliari on 17 June 2010, under request of Serie A giants [[A.C. Milan|Milan]], who were interested in appointing him as their new manager.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cagliaricalcio.net/news/notizia.asp?idNotizia=8813&type=0&id_menu=1 |publisher=Cagliari Calcio |language=Italian |accessdate=17 June 2010 |date=17 June 2010 |title=Il Cagliari libera Allegri |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620211751/http://www.cagliaricalcio.net/news/notizia.asp?idNotizia=8813&type=0&id_menu=1 |archivedate=20 June 2010 }}</ref> On 25 June, Allegri was officially appointed as the new manager of Milan. In his first season in charge, Allegri led Milan to their first championship title since [[2003\u201304 Serie A|2004]], beating title incumbents and [[Derby della Madonnina|cross-city rivals]] [[Inter Milan]] in both league fixtures;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/9479355.stm|title=AC Milan win first Serie A since 2004 with draw at Roma|publisher=BBC|date=7 May 2011|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref> at the time, only [[Roberto Mancini]] had achieved that feat at a younger age.<ref name=relationship/> Allegri's Milan side, however, failed to make it past the [[2010\u201311 Coppa Italia|semi-finals of the Coppa Italia]], losing to [[U.S. Citt\u00e0 di Palermo|Palermo]] 4\u20133 on aggregate. The team also qualified for the knockout stage of the [[2010\u201311 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]], where they were eliminated by [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]].\n\nSuccess continued in his second season at the club. He led Milan to their sixth [[Supercoppa Italiana]] title, by coming from behind in a 2\u20131 win over city rivals Internazionale in a game played at the [[Beijing National Stadium]] on 6 August [[2011 Supercoppa Italiana|2011]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gazzettaworld.gazzetta.it/features/ac-milan-past-allegri-juventus/|title=Echoes of AC Milan past loom over Allegri and Juventus|publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport|author1=Paolo Bandini|date=5 August 2015|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref> That was as far as his success went for that season, however. A semi-final [[Coppa Italia]] knockout at the hands of [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] followed by a quarter-final [[2011\u201312 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]] knockout at the hands of [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] left Milan fighting on only one front towards the end of the season\u2014the [[Scudetto]]. Even that was to be lost, however, with the ''Rossoneri'' finishing in second place to Juventus and therefore qualifying for [[2012\u201313 UEFA Champions League|next season's Champions League group stage]]. The season was also marked with controversy however, as in the second half of the season, Milan had a goal by [[Sulley Muntari]] disallowed in a key match against title rivals Juventus at the [[San Siro]], after they had already been leading 1\u20130; the match eventually ended in a 1\u20131 draw.<ref name=relationship/> Along with [[Adriano Galliani]], Allegri drew criticism for his decision to sell veteran deep-lying playmaker Andrea Pirlo to Juventus, after excluding him from the starting eleven the previous season, and deeming him to be a surplus due to his age; Pirlo went on to play a key role in Juventus's victorious Serie A title.<ref name=relationship/>\n\nOn 13 January 2012, Allegri agreed to extend his contract with Milan to the end of 2013\u201314 season. On 5 June 2012, Allegri stated that he intends to coach for only 10 more years and plans to retire at the age of 55 due to the fact that coaching contains a high level of stress and anxiety. He also said that he hopes to coach the Italian national side before he retires. With the departure and retirement of several of the club's key players, Milan struggled at the beginning of the 2012\u201313 season, and had only collected 8 points from their first 7 games, putting Allegri in danger of getting fired early on.<ref name=relationship/> Despite all the criticism from the critics, Milan stuck with Allegri and he managed to get the best out of some younger players including [[Stephan El Shaarawy]], Milan's home-grown player [[Mattia De Sciglio]] and later on [[Mario Balotelli]]. Allegri managed to steer the Rossoneri from 16th place to a 3rd-place finish at the end of the season, with an epic 2\u20131 comeback victory away to [[A.C. Siena|Siena]]. The result gave Milan a spot in the playoff round for the [[2013\u201314 UEFA Champions League|2013\u201314 Champions League]] campaign.<ref name=relationship/>\n\nOn 1 June 2013, club president [[Silvio Berlusconi]] confirmed Allegri to remain as the manager of Milan, despite numerous speculations that he would be given the sack. On 31 December 2013, Allegri confirmed he would leave the club at the end of the season, telling ''Gazzetta dello Sport'': \"Of course this is my last Christmas at A.C. Milan\". However, Milan reported that Allegri and his staff were relieved of their duties with immediate effect on 13 January 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.acmilan.com/en/news/breaking_news_show/52094 |publisher=AC Milan |accessdate=13 January 2014 |date=13 January 2014 |title=A.C. MILAN OFFICIAL COMMUNICATION}}</ref>\n\n=== Juventus ===\nOn 16 July 2014, Allegri was appointed as the new head coach of [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]], replacing [[Antonio Conte]] who had resigned the day before.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/28327574|title=Juventus hire former AC Milan boss Massimiliano Allegri|work= BBC Sport|date=16 July 2014|accessdate=16 July 2014}}</ref> Although the decision to hire Allegri was initially met with ambivalence,<ref name=relationship/> on 2 May 2015, he guided Juventus to their fourth consecutive [[2014\u201315 Serie A|Serie A title]], as the club defeated [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] 1\u20130 at the [[Stadio Luigi Ferraris]] in Genoa; this was only the second time Juventus had won four consecutive [[Scudetto]] titles (the last time being from 1931 to 1935, when they won five Scudetto titles in a row). Having previously won the title with [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] in 2011, it also marked his second Scudetto title as a manager in [[Serie A]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/italian-serie-a/12/blog/post/2431800/max-allegri-vindicated-by-juventus-serie-a-title|title=Vindication for Max Allegri as Juventus claim fourth consecutive Italian title|publisher=ESPN FC|author1=James Horncastle|date=3 May 2015|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref> On 13 May 2015, Allegri guided Juventus to the [[2015 UEFA Champions League Final|Champions League final]] by defeating defending champions [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] in the semifinals, 3\u20132 on aggregate;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-3080482/Real-Madrid-1-1-Juventus-agg-2-3-Alvaro-Morata-cancels-Cristiano-Ronaldo-penalty-haunt-former-club-Serie-giants-reach-Champions-League-final.html|title=Real Madrid 1-1 Juventus (agg 2-3): Alvaro Morata cancels out Cristiano Ronaldo penalty to haunt former club and send Serie A giants into Champions League final against Barcelona|work=Mail Online}}</ref> it had been twelve years since the Bianconeri had last appeared in the final, eventually losing to Milan 3\u20132 on penalties in [[2003 UEFA Champions League Final|2003]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/blog/the-match/60/post/2445637/juvetus-outlast-real-madrid-to-reach-champions-league-final|title=Juventus overcome shaky start to outlast Real Madrid and reach final|publisher=ESPN FC|author1=Dermot Corrigan|date=13 May 2015|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref> A week later, on 20 May 2015, Allegri guided Juventus to a domestic [[Double (association football)|double]] by helping the club win their record tenth [[2015 Coppa Italia Final|Coppa Italia]], defeating [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]] 2\u20131 in [[Overtime (sports)|extra time]]. The Old Lady last won the trophy in 1995, breaking their twenty-year drought of having not won the competition, and making them the first team in Italy to win the trophy ten times.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2015/matches/round=2000552/match=2015227/prematch/preview/index.html#juventus+barcelona+preview|title=UEFA Champions League final preview|publisher=UEFA.com|date=5 June 2015|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref> On 6 June 2015, Juventus were defeated by [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]], 3\u20131, in the 2015 [[UEFA Champions League]] [[2015 UEFA Champions League Final|final]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/jun/06/barcelona-juventus-luis-suarez|title=Luis Su\u00e1rez\u2019s strike rewards Barcelona\u2019s dominance to break Juventus|work=The Guardian|author1=Daniel Taylor|date=6 June 2015|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 July 2015, almost a year after signing with Juventus, Allegri signed a one-year extension to his current contract keeping him at the club until the end of the 2016\u201317 season. On 8 August 2015, Allegri led Juventus to a 2\u20130 victory over Lazio in the [[2015 Supercoppa Italiana|Supercoppa Italiana]], with new signings [[Mario Mand\u017euki\u0107]] and [[Paulo Dybala]] scoring the goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gazzettaworld.gazzetta.it/news/serie-a/juventus/allegri-season-starts-now/|title=Allegri: Juventus' season starts now|publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport|author1=Padraig Whelan|date=11 September 2015|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref> Allegri was included in the 10-man shortlist of nominees for the [[2015 FIFA Ballon d'Or#FIFA World Coach of the Year for Men.27s Football|2015 FIFA World Coach of the Year Award]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gazzettaworld.gazzetta.it/news/serie-a/juventus/allegri-coach-of-year/|title=Allegri nominated for FIFA World Coach of the Year award|publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport|author1=Ogo Sylla|date=20 October 2015|accessdate=30 November 2015}}</ref> but was later not included among the three finalists, despite almost completing a treble in his first season as Juventus's coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/76477/allegri-snubbed-coach-year|title=Allegri snubbed for Coach of the Year|publisher=Football Italia|date=30 November 2015|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref> However, on 14 December 2015, Allegri won the [[Serie A Coach of the Year]] award;<ref name=\"Sport Mediaset\">{{cite news|last1=Riggio|first1=Salvatore|title=Gran Gal\u00e0 del Calcio: \u00e8 dominio Juve, miglior squadra e miglior allenatore|url=http://www.sportmediaset.mediaset.it/calcio/calcio/gran-gala-del-calcio-e-dominio-juve-miglior-squadra-e-miglior-allenatore_1084196-201502a.shtml|accessdate=15 December 2015|work=Sport Mediaset|date=14 December 2015|language=it}}</ref> and later on 7 March 2016, his second ever [[Panchina d'Oro]] for his success with Juventus during the 2014\u201315 season.<ref name=juvepanchia>{{cite web|url=http://www.juventus.com/en/news/news/2016/allegri-wins-panchina-doro-award-.php|title=Allegri wins 'Panchina d\u2019Oro' award|publisher=Juventus.com|date=7 March 2016|accessdate=7 March 2016}}</ref> On 25 April, Juventus were crowned [[2015\u201316 Serie A]] champions; after initially struggling during the first ten league matches of the season, Juventus went on an unbeaten streak and won 24 of their next 25 league games to come back from 12th place to defend the title.<ref name=\"Juventus retain Scudetto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/83381/official-juventus-retain-scudetto|title=Official: Juventus retain Scudetto!|publisher=Football Italia|date=25 April 2016|accessdate=25 April 2016}}</ref> The team's unbeaten streak ended after 26 matches, and was broken following a 2\u20131 away loss to [[Hellas Verona F.C.|Verona]] on 8 May.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/84053/allegri-enough-celebrating-now|title=Allegri: 'Enough celebrating now!'|publisher=Football Italia|date=8 May 2016|accessdate=9 May 2016}}</ref> On 6 May, Allegri extended his contract as Juventus manager to 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.juventus.com/en/news/news/2016/allegri-extends-juventus-contract-.php|title=Allegri extends Juventus contract|publisher=juventus.com|date=6 May 2016|accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref> On 21 May, he led Juventus to the domestic double once again after a 1\u20130 victory over Milan in the [[2016 Coppa Italia Final]], the first team in Italy to win back-to-back doubles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36211846|title=AC Milan 0-1 Juventus (aet)|publisher=bbc.com|date=21 May 2016|accessdate=21 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 May 2017, Allegri led Juventus to their [[2016\u201317 Coppa Italia|12th Coppa Italia title]] in a 2\u20130 win over Lazio, becoming the first team to win three consecutive championships.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beinsports.com/au/football/news/juventus-wins-historic-third-straight-coppa-i/543055|title=JUVENTUS WINS HISTORIC THIRD STRAIGHT COPPA ITALIA|publisher=beinsports.com|date=17 May 2017|accessdate=17 May 2017}}</ref> Four days later on 21 May, following a 3\u20130 win over Crotone, Juventus secured their sixth consecutive Serie A title, establishing an all-time record of successive triumphs in the competition.<ref name=\"Giocatori pluriscudettati\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/it/notizie/giocatori-pluriscudettati-buffon-raggiunge-la-vetta-con-8/xnk18vgwb73c1xgwrr10bgj4a|title=Giocatori pluriscudettati, Buffon raggiunge la vetta con 8: Bonucci a 7|publisher=Goal.com|language=Italian|date=21 May 2017|accessdate=21 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/italian-serie-a/story/3130448/juventus-clinch-sixth-consecutive-serie-a-title-against-crotone|title=Juventus Clinch Sixth Consecutive Serie A Title Against Crotone|publisher=espnfc.us|date=21 May 2017|accessdate=21 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.juventus.com/en/news/news/2017/juventus-champions-of-italy-for-the-sixth-time-in-a-row.php|title=Juventus, Champions of Italy for the sixth time in a row|publisher=[[Juventus F.C.|juventus.com]]|date=21 May 2017}}</ref> On 3 June 2017, Allegri entered his [[2017 UEFA Champions League Final|second Champions League Final]] in three years with Juventus, but suffered a 4\u20131 defeat to defending champions Real Madrid.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/jun/03/juventus-real-madrid-champions-league-final-match-report |title=Real Madrid and Cristiano Ronaldo see off Juventus to win Champions League |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=3 June 2017 |accessdate=3 June 2017}}</ref> On 7 June, Allegri renewed his contract with Juventus until 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/103778/official-allegri-renews-juventus|title=Official: Allegri renews with Juventus|publisher=Football Italia|date=7 June 2017|accessdate=7 June 2017}}</ref> Allegri took charge of his 200th game with Juventus on 9 February 2018, a 2\u20130 away win over [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/buffon-makes-500th-juventus-league-appearance/m6jy2e1h011412yy7avzz7n0i|title=Buffon makes 500th Juventus league appearance|publisher=Goal.com|author1=Ryan Benson|date=9 February 2018|accessdate=9 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://it.eurosport.com/calcio/serie-a/2017-2018/l-ex-bernardeschi-e-higuain-la-juventus-vince-2-0-a-firenze_sto6598839/story.shtml|title=L'ex Bernardeschi e Higuain: la Juventus vince 2-0 a Firenze|publisher=Eurosport|language=Italian|author1=Enrico Turcato|date=9 February 2018|accessdate=9 February 2018}}</ref> On 9 May 2018, Allegri won his [[2018 Coppa Italia Final|fourth consecutive Coppa Italia title]], in a 4\u20130 win over Milan.<ref name=four>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/121138/coppa-force-four-juve-flatten-milan|title=Coppa: Force Four Juve flatten Milan|publisher=Football Italia|date=9 May 2018}}</ref> Four days later on 13 May, following a 0\u20130 draw with Roma, Allegri secured his fourth consecutive Serie A title, becoming the first manager in Europe's top five leagues to win four consecutive doubles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/121329/juventus-seven|title=Juventus Seven-Up|publisher=Football Italia|date=13 May 2018}}</ref> On 17 May 2019, after Juventus had already secured its fifth straight Scudetto under Allegri on 20 April, Juventus announced that he would leave the club at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/137199/juventus-fightback-secure-scudetto|title=Juventus fightback to secure Scudetto|publisher=Football Italia|date=20 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.juventus.com/en/news/news/2019/statement-from-club.php|title=Statement from the club|publisher=juventus.com|date=17 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Style of management ==\nAllegri has been praised for his tactical intelligence and his ability to build effectively upon [[Antonio Conte]]'s successful tactics and winning mentality as Juventus's manager, albeit in a less rigorous manner. He initially continued to use Conte's trademark [[Formation (association football)#3\u20135\u20132|3\u20135\u20132 formation]], but later switched to a four-man back-line, in particular in the UEFA Champions League. Under Allegri, Juventus became slightly less aggressive and intense in their pressing off the ball while their playing style became more patient and focussed on keeping possession and gaining territorial advantage in order to conserve energy, tactics which he had previously used while at Milan. Although Allegri's team was still effective at winning the ball in midfield and scoring from counter-attacks, the club's attacking play on the ball usually involved a slower build-up, which mainly consisted of short passes, and fewer long balls from [[Andrea Pirlo|Pirlo]] and [[Leonardo Bonucci|Bonucci]].<ref name=stamp>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/60374/allegri%E2%80%99s-stamp-bianconeri|title=Allegri\u2019s stamp on the Bianconeri|publisher=Football Italia|author1=Luca Cetta|date=28 December 2014|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=imagination>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/54899/%E2%80%98more-imagination-allegri%E2%80%99|title=More imagination with Allegri|publisher=Football Italia|date=26 August 2014|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acmilan.com/en/news/show/144150|title=THE NUMBERS GAME|publisher=A.C. Milan|date=30 October 2012|accessdate=26 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Mentality\">{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/83464/%E2%80%98mentality-change-thanks-allegri%E2%80%99|title=Mentality change thanks to Allegri|publisher=Football Italia|date=27 April 2016|accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref> Goalkeeper [[Gianluigi Buffon|Buffon]] also continued to primarily play the ball out from the back with short ground passes to the defenders, but he also began to use deeper goal kicks out to the wings.<ref name=beginnings>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/beginnings-massimiliano-allegris-juventus-193423684.html|title=New beginnings for Massimiliano Allegri's Juventus|publisher=Yahoo.com|date=18 September 2014|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/news/marchisio-allegri-will-boost-juve-europe#:LPvqxKlWfABWPA|title=Marchisio: Allegri will boost Juve in Europe|publisher=FourFourTwo|date=26 August 2014|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=superpower>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurosport.com/football/champions-league/2012-2013/how-massimo-allegri-made-juventus-a-european-superpower-once-more_sto4768346/story.shtml|title=How Massimo Allegri made Juventus a European superpower once more|publisher=Eurosport|author1=Greg Lea|date=4 June 2015|accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref> Allegri has also been lauded for his versatility, which he demonstrated by adopting and switching between several different formations during his first season with Juventus, including the [[Formation (association football)#4\u20133\u20131\u20132|4\u20133\u20131\u20132]], the [[Formation (association football)#4\u20134\u20132|4\u20134\u20132]] and the [[Formation (association football)#4\u20133\u20133|4\u20133\u20133 formations]],<ref name=imagination/><ref name=conundrum>{{cite web|url=http://gazzettaworld.gazzetta.it/news/serie-a/juventus/allegri-tactical-conundrum/|title=Allegri and the Juventus tactical conundrum|publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport|author1=Ogo Sylla|date=21 November 2015|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref> which he had also previously adopted while at Milan<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/24398/milan-and-4-3-3-system|title=Milan and the 4-3-3 system|publisher=Football Italia|author1=David Swan|date=28 August 2012|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref> in order to find the most suitable system for his players.<ref name=\"top\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2238393.html|title=How Juventus got back to the top|publisher=UEFA.com|author1=Paolo Menicucci|date=23 April 2015|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref> The fluidity of Juventus's formations under Allegri allowed talented players more freedom and creative licence<ref name=stamp/><ref name=imagination/> and enabled the midfielders to make attacking runs into the area.<ref name=\"top\"/><ref name=\"title intentions\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/club/juventus/111/blog/post/2751456/juventus-can-can-announce-title-intentions-vs-fiorentina|title=Juventus can can announce title intentions with Fiorentina win|publisher=ESPN FC|author1=Mina Rzouki|date=11 December 2015|accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref> Despite implementing several changes, Allegri still managed to preserve Juventus's defensive organisation and strength\u2014this was further demonstrated by his tendency to switch to the 3\u20135\u20132 in the final 20 minutes of closely contested matches in order to hold on to the result<ref name=superpower/><ref name=\"top\"/> as well as by his tendency to play behind the ball with two deep, tight defensive lines when facing teams that dominated possession, preferring instead to focus on breaking up play and adopting a counter-attacking style of play similar to that which he had previously also used with Milan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/67389/allegris-berlin-battle-plan|title=Allegri's Berlin battle plan|publisher=Football Italia|author1=Gaby McKay|date=5 June 2015|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/juventus/story/2755330/juventus-are-back-in-serie-a-race-says-massimiliano-allegri|title=Juventus are back in Serie A race, says boss Massimiliano Allegri|publisher=ESPN FC|date=13 December 2015|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Ode\">{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/83365/ode-allegri|title=An Ode to Allegri|publisher=Football Italia|author1=Edo Dalmonte|date=25 April 2016|accessdate=26 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nPirlo praised Allegri's seemingly more relaxed attitude to coaching stating that he \"brought a sense of calm\" to the team and that he aided in endowing the players with a sense of confidence.<ref name=\"top\"/> Regarding Juventus's fluidity under Allegri, Italian football analyst Antonio Gagliardi tweeted: \"Juventus defend low with a [[Formation (association football)#5\u20134\u20131|5\u20134\u20131]], they press with a 4\u20134\u20132 and they attack with a [[Formation (association football)#4\u20132\u20133\u20131|4\u20132\u20133\u20131]]. Systems in the future will become ever more fluid\".<ref name=credit>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/uefa-champions-league/2/blog/post/2831403/credit-pep-guardiola-max-allegri-bayern-munich-and-juventus|title=Pep Guardiola, Max Allegri, Bayern Munich and Juventus all deserve credit|publisher=ESPN FC|author1=Gabriele Marcotti|date=17 March 2016|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref> In his second season with the club, Allegri was praised for rebuilding the team following the departure of several key players, such as Pirlo, [[Arturo Vidal|Vidal]] and [[Carlos Tevez|Tevez]]; and for his role in inspiring Juventus to a comeback to defend the league title, which included a 15-match winning streak after a negative start.<ref name=\"Mentality\"/><ref name=\"trionfo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/Juventus/23-04-2016/juve-allegri-scudetto-supercoppa-campionato-champions-bayern-napoli-150347287662.shtml|title=Juve, Allegri e la rivoluzione indolore. Un trionfo firmato Max|publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|author1=Alberto Mauro|date=25 April 2016|accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/82507/allegri-%E2%80%98juventus-ignore-controversy%E2%80%99|title=Allegri: 'Juventus ignore controversy'|publisher=Football Italia|date=8 April 2016|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref> Although a 1\u20130 defeat to Sassuolo on 28 October 2015 left them in 12th place, 11 points from the top of the table after their first 10 league matches, Juventus went unbeaten in their next 25 fixtures, winning 24 of them and finished the season as 2015\u201316 Serie A champions with three games to spare\u2014this was the club's record fifth consecutive league title since the 2011\u201312 season.<ref name=\"Juventus retain Scudetto\"/><ref name=\"Ode\"/><ref name=\"trionfo\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=2357383.html|title=Juventus win fifth straight Serie A title|publisher=UEFA.com|author1=Paolo Menicucci|date=25 April 2016|accessdate=25 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2016\u201317 season, Allegri drew further praise in the media for his decision to occasionally depart from the team's trademark 3\u20135\u20132 formation and instead adopt a new 4\u20132\u20133\u20131 formation, in particular for European matches, a system which better suited the characteristics of the club's new signings\u2014the tactical switch most notably saw [[Gonzalo Higua\u00edn]] fielded as the team's main striker while Dybala was used in a more creative role as number 10, backed by two central box-to-box midfielders (usually the more defensive-minded [[Sami Khedira]] alongside either [[Miralem Pjani\u0107]] or [[Claudio Marchisio]] in a deeper playmaking role) and flanked by [[Juan Cuadrado]] on the right wing. The switch to a four-man back-line also allowed Allegri to rotate several players, such as centre-backs [[Giorgio Chiellini]], [[Andrea Barzagli]] and Leonardo Bonucci as well as right-backs [[Dani Alves]] and [[Stephan Lichtsteiner]], while centre-forward Mario Mand\u017euki\u0107 was deployed in a deeper, wider role as a [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]] or attacking midfielder on the left flank\u2014this new position utilised the Croatian's work-rate, intelligence, hold-up play and ability to cover for teammates making overlapping runs, in particular those of left-back [[Alex Sandro]] while Mand\u017euki\u0107's height and ability in the air also enabled him to function essentially as a \"[[Forward (association football)#Centre-forward|target man]]\" in wider areas.\n\nJuventus's tactical versatility was demonstrated by their ability to switch between the 3\u20135\u20132 and 4\u20132\u20133\u20131 formations during matches; this trait was particularly evident in the team's first leg fixture of the Champions League semi-final against [[A.S. Monaco|Monaco]]. Ahead of the match, Allegri fielded Dani Alves as a right-sided wing-back in a 3\u20135\u20132 formation in lieu of Cuadrado and reverted to the team's trademark back-three composed of Barzagli, Bonucci and Chiellini. When in possession, Juventus kept the ball and played it out from the back and usually attacked with a [[Formation (association football)#3\u20136\u20131|3\u20132\u20134\u20131]], [[Formation (association football)#3\u20134\u20133|3\u20134\u20133]] or 4\u20132\u20133\u20131 formation as Dani Alves often made offensive overlapping runs behind the opposition's defence, essentially acting as a winger, which created difficulties for Monaco's back-line while Barzagli moved out wide to cover for the Brazilian, functioning as a makeshift right-back. When defending behind the ball, the team reverted to an organised 3\u20135\u20132 or [[Formation (association football)#5\u20133\u20132|5\u20133\u20132 formation]], which was difficult for Monaco to break down, courtesy of the strength of Juventus's defensive trio, who were dubbed \"the [[BBC (disambiguation)|BBC]]\" in the media, a reference to the defenders' initials\u2014Juventus's defensive solidity ensured that the club only conceded three goals en route to the 2017 Champions League final and also allowed the Turin side to create goalscoring opportunities from swift, sudden and efficient counter-attacks after winning back possession. Juventus ended the season by capturing their third consecutive domestic double, which included an unprecedented Italian record sixth consecutive league title; and also reached the Champions League final for the second time in three years, losing out 4\u20131 to defending champions Real Madrid.<ref name=\"Galatasaray go for Mandzukic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/99125/galatasaray-go-mandzukic|title=Galatasaray go for Mandzukic|publisher=Football Italia|date=2 March 2017|accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/97325/audacious-juve-new-norm|title=Audacious Juve the new norm|publisher=Football Italia| first = Nick | last = Valerio|date=24 January 2017|accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/95794/west-ham-want-mandzukic-zaza|title=West Ham want Mandzukic for Zaza|publisher=Football Italia|date=17 December 2016|accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11675/10659388/who-could-tottenham-hotspur-target-in-january|title=Who could Tottenham Hotspur target in January?|publisher=Sky Sports|date=6 November 2016|accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Mandzukic proving worth to Juventus\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/club/juventus/111/blog/post/3013358/mario-mandzukic-proving-worth-to-juventus-and-max-allegri-yet-again|title=Mario Mandzukic proving worth to Juventus and Max Allegri yet again|publisher=ESPN FC|first = Mina | last = Rzouki |date=6 December 2016|accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/97804/juventus-cant-forget-3-5-2|title=Juventus can't forget 3\u20135\u20132|publisher=Football Italia| first = Gaby | last = McKay|date=2 February 2017|accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.acmilan.com/en/news/first-team/2017-03-08/opponents-under-the-microscope-juventus|title= OPPONENTS UNDER THE MICROSCOPE: JUVENTUS |publisher=A.C. Milan|date=8 March 2017|accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsoccer.com/features/audacious-allegri-has-juventus-back-on-track-394594|title=Paddy Agnew\u2019s Notes from Italy: audacious Allegri has Juventus back on track|publisher=World Soccer| first = Paddy | last = Agnew|date=23 January 2017|accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beinsports.com/hk/serie-a/news/allegri-admits-new-juventus-formation-was-a-3/430290|title= Allegri admits new Juventus formation was a 'mad idea' |publisher=beINSports|date=22 January 2017|accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/club/juventus/111/blog/post/2963954/as-dybala-and-higuain-learn-to-coexist-allegri-must-get-creativity-from-rest-of-juventus|title=As Dybala and Higuain learn to coexist, Juventus need goals from elsewhere|publisher=ESPN FC| first = Mina | last = Rzouki |date=1 October 2016|accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/100616/allegris-ultimate-tactical-test|title=Allegri's ultimate tactical test|publisher=Football Italia|author1=Greg Murray|date=4 April 2017|accessdate=12 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zonalmarking.net/2017/05/05/monaco-0-2-juventus-allegri-uses-wing-backs-and-alves-creates-both-goals-for-higuain/|title=Monaco 0-2 Juventus: Allegri uses wing-backs and Alves creates both goals for Higuain|publisher=zonalmarking.net|date=5 May 2017|accessdate=12 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/05/03/monaco-vs-juventus-champions-league-live-score-updates/|title=Monaco 0 Juventus 2: Gonzalo Higuain scores twice as experienced Italians take control of the tie|work=The Telegraph|author1=JJ Bull|date=3 May 2017|accessdate=12 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurosport.com/football/serie-a/2016-2017/juventus-coach-massimiliano-allegri-renews-contract-until-2020_sto6204570/story.shtml|title=Juventus coach Massimiliano Allegri renews contract until 2020|publisher=Eurosport.com|date=7 June 2017|accessdate=12 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://it.eurosport.com/calcio/champions-league/2016-2017/le-5-verita-che-ci-ha-lasciato-monaco-juventus_sto6152236/story.shtml|title=Le 5 verit\u00e0 che ci ha lasciato Monaco-Juventus|publisher=Eurosport.com|author1=Enrico Turcato|language=Italian|date=4 May 2017|accessdate=12 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2017/matches/round=2000787/match=2019641/prematch/background/|title=Juventus and Real Madrid face final showdown|publisher=UEFA.com|date=19 May 2017|accessdate=12 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Managerial statistics ==\n{{updated|26 May 2019}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Team\n!rowspan=2|From\n!rowspan=2|To\n!colspan=8|Record\n|-\n!{{Tooltip|G|Games managed}